```{r fig1, out.width= "80%", fig.cap = "Left panel (A): Percentage of people who report vote intention or sympathy towards Vox across time. Source: CIS Barometer data. Right panel (B): Percentage of seats Vox controls at the end of each year, by type of election (2015-2021). Source: Spanish electoral authorities.", fig.align = 'center', eval = TRUE}

knitr::include_graphics("Figures/Preliminary/Figure1.png")

```

As has been established, events such as elections provide a highly publicized scenario and, in addition to being a mechanism for the election of political representatives, they function as a cue which provides citizens with information about the distribution of preferences in society [@BISCHOF_WAGNER1_2019; @VALENTIM1_2021].

The argument for having chosen a regional election and not a general one for this study, even though regional elections could be considered as second-order elections, is twofold [@REIF_SCHMITT_NORRIS1_1997]. Firstly, these were the elections in which Vox obtained its first "big win", which was also the first time an RRP ever entered the Spanish political institutions since the reinstating of the Spanish democracy [@TURNBULL-DUGARTE1_2019]. On the other hand, the win for the political right in Andalucía that year spoiled what would have been the eleventh consecutive legislature for the main left party in Spain, Partido Socialista Obrero Español (PSOE), which had since 1982 held office in that Autonomous Community. Vox's support, thus, facilitated the formation of a right-wing government by Partido Popular (PP) and Ciudadanos (C's) for the first time in that region.

Many newspapers from different regions of Spain covered the news of the elections during the whole campaign, but also the day after the elections. Many newspaper covers had articles and headlines about the Andalusian elections, which shows the importance of these elections not only in Andalucía, but also in the rest of the country. However, Vox's entry had a much bigger role in Andalusian news outlets, often being the protagonist of their main headline (as can be seen in Figure \@ref(fig:figap1) of Appendix 1).

Additionally, for a descriptive preliminary analysis of the differentiated effect in Andalucía and the rest of Spain, the following line plot (Figure \@ref(fig:fig3)) shows how the entry of Vox into Andalusian institutions produced a peak of searches for the political party on Google both at the state and regional levels, followed by the peaks produced by the two general elections the following year.

```{r fig3, fig.cap="Google searches of the political party Vox in Andalucía and the rest of Spain for the last three years. Note: The dashed lines signify the date of the three main elections of 2018 and 2019 where Vox gained political representation. Source: Google Trends data.", out.width = "70%", fig.align = 'center'}
# VOX ESPA?A
googlestats.esp <- read.csv("Data/googletrends/VoxEspaña.csv",
                            header = FALSE,
                            sep = ",")

googlestats.esp <- googlestats.esp[-c(1,2),]
googlestats.esp$V1.rec <- as.Date(googlestats.esp$V1, tryFormats = ("%Y-%m-%d"))
googlestats.esp <- googlestats.esp[-1]
googlestats.esp$V2[googlestats.esp$V2 == "<1"] <- 0
googlestats.esp$V2.rec <- as.numeric(googlestats.esp$V2)
googlestats.esp <- googlestats.esp[-1]
names(googlestats.esp) <- c("date", "spain")


#### VOX ANDALUC?A

googlestats.and <- read.csv("Data/googletrends/VoxAndalucia.csv",
